  "prompt": "Is Kyiv (Kiev) radioactive?",
  "response": "Kyiv, the capital of Ukraine, is not considered to be radioactive in a harmful sense. However, the Chernobyl disaster of 1986, which occurred about 130 kilometers (approximately 80 miles) north of Kyiv, released significant amounts of radioactive material into the environment. \n\nFollowing the disaster, certain areas, especially within the Chernobyl Exclusion Zone, remain contaminated and are monitored for radiation levels. While parts of the region close to Chernobyl still have elevated radiation levels, Kyiv itself is generally safe for residents and visitors, with no widespread or high levels of radioactivity reported.\n\nThat said, it's always a good practice to stay informed about the health and safety conditions of any area, particularly in regions that have experienced significant industrial accidents in the past.",
